SENATE BILL 419
J2 6lr0775
CF HB 42
By: Senators Simonaire and Augustine
Introduced and read first time: January 29, 2026
Assigned to: Finance
Committee Report: Favorable
Senate action: Adopted
Read second time: February 12, 2026
CHAPTER ______
1 AN ACT concerning
2 Health Occupations – State Board of Massage Therapy Examiners – Revisions
3 FOR the purpose of authorizing an individual registered by the State Board of Massage
4 Therapy Examiners to practice massage therapy in the State to continue to practice
5 massage therapy beyond a certain date; altering the requirements an individual
6 must meet to qualify for a license to practice massage therapy; repealing obsolete
7 qualifications for registered massage practitioners; repealing the requirement that
8 the imposition of a certain administrative penalty be subject to certain hearing
9 requirements; altering certain reinstatement and reactivation requirements; and
10 generally relating to massage therapists.
11 BY repealing and reenacting, with amendments,
12 Article – Health Occupations
13 Section 6–301(a), 6–302, 6–305(d), 6–306, and 6–306.2
14 Annotated Code of Maryland
15 (2021 Replacement Volume and 2025 Supplement)
16 SECTION 1. BE IT ENACTED BY THE GENERAL ASSEMBLY OF MARYLAND,
17 That the Laws of Maryland read as follows:
18 Article – Health Occupations
19 6–301.
EXPLANATION: CAPITALS INDICATE MATTER ADDED TO EXISTING LAW.
[Brackets] indicate matter deleted from existing law.
Underlining indicates amendments to bill.
Strike out indicates matter stricken from the bill by amendment or deleted from the law by
amendment. *sb0419*

2 SENATE BILL 419
1 (a) Except as otherwise provided in this title, before an individual may practice
2 massage therapy in the State, the individual shall be:
3 (1) [On or before October 31, 2026:
4 (i)] Licensed by the Board; or
5 [(ii)] (2) Registered by the Board to practice massage therapy in a
6 setting that is not a health care setting[; or
7 (2) On or after November 1, 2026, licensed by the Board].
8 6–302.
9 (a) In this section, “contact hour” means 50 minutes of actual instructional time
10 per each 60–minute hour.
11 (b) To qualify for a license, an applicant shall be an individual who:
12 (1) Is of good moral character;
13 (2) Is at least 18 years old;
14 (3) [Has] EXCEPT AS PROVIDED IN SUBSECTION (C) OF THIS SECTION,
15 HAS graduated from an institution of postsecondary education, as defined in § 10–101 of
16 the Education Article and approved by the Maryland Higher Education Commission, with
17 at least 750 contact hours of education in a curriculum:
18 (i) Approved by the Board;
19 (ii) Endorsed by:
20 1. The Commission on Massage Therapy Accreditation; or
21 2. An equivalent entity that accredits both institutions of
22 higher education and programs offering instruction in massage therapy; and
23 (iii) Accredited by an institutional accreditation agency recognized by
24 [the]:
25 1. THE United States Department of Education; OR
26 2. ANOTHER ENTITY THAT ACCREDITS PROGRAMS
27 OFFERING INSTRUCTION IN MASSAGE THERAPY;

SENATE BILL 419 3
1 (4) [Has] EXCEPT AS PROVIDED IN SUBSECTION (C) OF THIS SECTION,
2 HAS completed 750 contact hours of education in a Board–approved program for the study
3 of massage therapy that includes the following areas of content:
4 (i) Anatomy, physiology, and kinesiology;
5 (ii) Massage therapy theory;
6 (iii) Contraindications and pathology;
7 (iv) Professional ethics;
8 (v) Health and hygiene;
9 (vi) Research;
10 (vii) Supervised hands–on techniques; and
11 (viii) Clinical assessment and documentation;
12 (5) Has passed an examination approved by the Board; and
13 (6) Submits to a criminal history records check in accordance with § 6–303
14 of this subtitle.
