14 (C) (1) AN APPLICANT WHO HAS GRADUATED FROM AN OUT–OF–STATE
15 PROGRAM FOR THE STUDY OF MASSAGE THERAPY SHALL HAVE GRADUATED FROM A
16 PROGRAM FOR THE STUDY OF MASSAGE THERAPY THAT:
17 (I) HAS BEEN APPROVED BY THE STATE’S HIGHER EDUCATION
18 COMMISSION OR SIMILAR ENTITY THAT REGULATES INSTITUTIONS OF
19 POSTSECONDARY EDUCATION;
20 (II) HAS BEEN ENDORSED BY:
21 1. THE COMMISSION ON MASSAGE THERAPY
22 ACCREDITATION; OR
23 2. AN EQUIVALENT ENTITY THAT IS AN ACCREDITING
24 AGENCY OR ORGANIZATION THAT ACCREDITS BOTH INSTITUTIONS OF HIGHER
25 EDUCATION AND PROGRAMS OFFERING INSTRUCTION IN MASSAGE THERAPY;
26 (III) IS ACCREDITED BY AN INSTITUTIONAL ACCREDITATION
27 AGENCY RECOGNIZED BY:

SENATE BILL 419 5
1 1. THE UNITED STATES DEPARTMENT OF EDUCATION;
2 OR
3 2. ANOTHER ENTITY THAT ACCREDITS PROGRAMS
4 OFFERING INSTRUCTION IN MASSAGE THERAPY; AND
5 (IV) SUBJECT TO PARAGRAPH (2) OF THIS SUBSECTION,
6 REQUIRES AT LEAST 750 CONTACT HOURS THAT INCLUDES THE AREAS OF CONTENT
7 REQUIRED UNDER SUBSECTION (B)(4) OF THIS SECTION.
8 (2) AN APPLICANT WHO HAS GRADUATED FROM AN OUT–OF–STATE
9 PROGRAM FOR THE STUDY OF MASSAGE THERAPY THAT DOES NOT MEET THE
10 CONTACT HOUR REQUIREMENT UNDER THIS SUBSECTION MAY SUPPLEMENT THE
11 REQUIRED HOURS WITH:
12 (I) CONTACT HOURS FROM A BOARD–APPROVED PROGRAM OF
13 STUDY OF MASSAGE THERAPY, ON A 1–HOUR TO 1–HOUR BASIS;
14 (II) BOARD–APPROVED CONTINUING EDUCATION HOURS, ON A
15 1–HOUR TO 1–HOUR BASIS; OR
16 (III) DOCUMENTED EVIDENCE OF HAVING COMPLETED AT LEAST
17 1,000 LICENSED, OUT–OF–STATE HOURS OF HANDS–ON MASSAGE THERAPY
18 EXPERIENCE WITHIN THE IMMEDIATELY PRECEDING 2 YEARS.
19 (d) (1) Subject to paragraph (2) of this subsection, the Board may waive any
20 requirement of this subtitle for an applicant who is licensed, certified, or registered to
21 practice massage therapy in another state.
22 (2) The Board may grant a waiver under paragraph (1) of this subsection
23 only if the applicant:
24 (i) Pays the application fee set by the Board; and
25 (ii) Provides adequate evidence that the applicant:
26 1. Has completed educational requirements that the Board
27 determines to be equivalent to the Board–approved educational requirements in this State;
28 2. At the time the applicant became licensed, certified, or
29 registered in the other state, passed in that state or any other state an examination that
30 the Board determines to be equivalent to the examination required in this State; and
31 3. Is of good moral character.

6 SENATE BILL 419
1 (e) On or after October 1, 2024, the Board may not issue an initial registration to
2 practice as a registered massage practitioner.
3 (f) [On or before October 31, 2026, the] THE Board shall convert the registration
4 of an individual registered by the Board as a registered massage practitioner to a license
5 to practice massage therapy if the individual complies with regulations adopted by the
6 Board.
7 6–305.
8 (d) (1) Each licensed massage therapist or registered massage practitioner
9 shall notify the Board in writing of any change in the name or address of the licensed
10 massage therapist or registered massage practitioner within 60 days after the change
11 occurred.
12 (2) [Subject to the hearing provisions of § 6–309 of this subtitle, if] IF a
13 licensed massage therapist or registered massage practitioner fails to notify the Board
14 within the time required under this subsection, the Board may impose an administrative
15 penalty of $100.
16 6–306.
17 (a) If a licensed massage therapist or registered massage practitioner fails for any
18 reason to renew a license or registration, the Board shall reinstate the license or
19 registration if the former licensed massage therapist or former registered massage
20 practitioner:
21 (1) Applies to the Board for reinstatement of the license or registration
22 within 5 years after the license or registration expires;
23 (2) Meets the renewal requirements of § 6–305 of this subtitle;
24 (3) Submits to the Board satisfactory evidence of having completed a State
25 and national criminal history records check in accordance with § 6–303 of this subtitle; and
26 (4) Pays to the Board the reinstatement fee set by the Board.
27 (b) (1) [The] EXCEPT AS PROVIDED IN PARAGRAPH (2) OR (3) OF THIS
28 SUBSECTION, THE Board may not reinstate the license of a former licensed massage
29 therapist or registration of a former registered massage practitioner who fails to apply for
30 reinstatement of the license or registration within 5 years after the license or registration
31 expires.
32 (2) [If the Board does not reinstate a license or registration under
33 paragraph (1) of this subsection, a] A former licensed massage therapist [or former
34 registered massage practitioner] may apply for a new license [or registration] by meeting

SENATE BILL 419 7
1 the licensing [or registration] requirements in effect at the time of application for obtaining
2 a new license [or registration] under this title and any additional requirements determined
3 by the Board.
4 (3) A FORMER REGISTERED MASSAGE PRACTITIONER WHO FAILS TO
5 APPLY FOR REINSTATEMENT OF THE REGISTRATION WITHIN 5 YEARS AFTER THE
6 REGISTRATION EXPIRES MAY BE REINSTATED ONLY BY MEETING THE LICENSING
7 REQUIREMENTS IN EFFECT FOR OBTAINING A NEW LICENSE UNDER THIS TITLE AND
8 ANY ADDITIONAL REQUIREMENTS DETERMINED BY THE BOARD.
9 6–306.2.
10 (a) The Board shall place a licensed massage therapist or registered massage
11 practitioner on inactive status if the licensee or registration holder submits to the Board:
12 (1) An application for inactive status on the form required by the Board;
13 and
14 (2) The inactive status fee set by the Board.
15 (b) A licensed massage therapist or a registered massage practitioner on inactive
16 status may reactivate the license or registration if the licensee or registration holder:
17 (1) Complies with the continuing education and CPR requirements that
18 are:
19 (i) Established in regulations adopted by the Board; and
20 (ii) In effect for the current license or registration renewal period in
21 which the licensee or registration holder seeks to reactivate the license or registration;
22 [and]
23 (2) SUBMITS TO THE BOARD SATISFACTORY EVIDENCE OF HAVING
24 COMPLETED A STATE AND NATIONAL CRIMINAL HISTORY RECORDS CHECK IN
25 ACCORDANCE WITH § 6–303 OF THIS SUBTITLE; AND
26 [(2)] (3) Pays the reactivation fee set by the Board.
27 (C) A REGISTERED MASSAGE PRACTITIONER ON INACTIVE STATUS WHO
28 FAILS TO REACTIVATE A REGISTRATION WITHIN 5 YEARS OF FIRST BEING PLACED
29 ON INACTIVE STATUS MAY REACTIVATE THE REGISTRATION ONLY BY MEETING THE
30 LICENSING REQUIREMENTS IN EFFECT FOR OBTAINING A NEW LICENSE UNDER THIS
31 TITLE AND ANY ADDITIONAL REQUIREMENTS DETERMINED BY THE BOARD.

8 SENATE BILL 419
